# 1️⃣ Sorting (`sort()`)

---

# First Understand the Problem

Suppose:

```text
50 10 30 20 40
```

Need:

```text
10 20 30 40 50
```

This process is called:

# Sorting

---

# Why Sorting Matters

Many difficult problems become easier after sorting.

Example:

```text
Find duplicates
Find closest numbers
Binary Search
Two Sum variations
```

Most start with sorting.

---

# C++ STL Solution

```cpp
#include <algorithm>

sort(arr, arr + n);
```

For vector:

```cpp
vector<int> v = {50,10,30,20};

sort(v.begin(), v.end());
```

Output:

```text
10 20 30 50
```

---

# Mental Model

Think of arranging books by roll number.

Before:

```text
40 10 30 20
```

After:

```text
10 20 30 40
```

Easy to search now.

---

# What Happens Internally?

You don't need to memorize the algorithm.

Just know:

```text
sort() = highly optimized STL sorting
```

Average complexity:

```text
O(n log n)
```

Very efficient.

---

# Descending Order

Default:

```text
Small → Large
```

Use:

```cpp
sort(v.begin(), v.end(), greater<int>());
```

Output:

```text
50 40 30 20
```

---

# Custom Comparator (Interview Favorite)

Suppose we want to sort students by marks.

```cpp
bool compare(int a, int b)
{
    return a > b;
}
```

Then:

```cpp
sort(v.begin(), v.end(), compare);
```

---

# Why Comparator Exists

Because sometimes:

```text
Normal sorting is not enough
```

Examples:

* Sort by age
* Sort by marks
* Sort by string length

---

# Mental Model

```text
Comparator = Sorting Rule
```

Like:

```text
School Rank Rule
```

The rule decides the order.

---

# Common Interview Question

### Why use STL sort?

Because:

```text
Fast
Optimized
Reliable
```

Never write your own sorting unless specifically asked.

---

# How to Remember

```text
sort() = Arrange Data
Comparator = Decide Rule
```

---

# 2️⃣ Binary Search (SUPER IMPORTANT)

---

# First Understand the Problem

Suppose numbers are:

```text
10 20 30 40 50 60 70
```

Need to find:

```text
50
```

---

# Method 1: Linear Search

Check one by one:

```text
10
20
30
40
50
```

Found.

Time Complexity:

```text
O(n)
```

---

# Problem

For:

```text
10,00,000 elements
```

Very slow.

---

# Better Idea

Look at middle element first.

This is:

# Binary Search

---

# Real-World Example

Think of a dictionary.

To find:

```text
Zebra
```

Do you start from page 1?

No.

You open near the middle.

Then eliminate half.

Repeat.

---

# Mental Model

```text
Binary Search = Keep Halving
```

---

# Example

Array:

```text
10 20 30 40 50 60 70
```

Find:

```text
60
```

---

### Step 1

Middle:

```text
40
```

---

Compare:

```text
60 > 40
```

So:

```text
Ignore left half
```

---

Remaining:

```text
50 60 70
```

---

### Step 2

Middle:

```text
60
```

Found.

---

# Why Binary Search Is Fast

Each step removes half.

```text
1000 elements
↓
500
↓
250
↓
125
↓
...
```

Very few operations.

---

# Time Complexity

```text
O(log n)
```

One of the fastest complexities.

---

# Important Requirement

⚠️ Array MUST be sorted.

Without sorting:

```text
30 10 50 20
```

Binary Search won't work.

---

# STL Binary Search

```cpp
binary_search(v.begin(), v.end(), 50);
```

Returns:

```text
true
```

or

```text
false
```

---

# Manual Binary Search

Interviewers often ask this.

```cpp
int low = 0;
int high = n - 1;

while(low <= high)
{
    int mid = (low + high) / 2;

    if(arr[mid] == target)
        return mid;

    else if(arr[mid] < target)
        low = mid + 1;

    else
        high = mid - 1;
}
```

Don't memorize yet.

Understand the idea:

```text
Check middle
Discard half
Repeat
```

---

# Visualization

Search:

```text
70
```

Array:

```text
10 20 30 40 50 60 70
```

Process:

```text
40
↓
Right Half

60
↓
Right Half

70
↓
Found
```

---

# Why Interviewers Love Binary Search

Because it tests:

* Logic
* Efficiency
* Problem solving

---

# Common Interview Question

### Linear Search Complexity?

```text
O(n)
```

---

### Binary Search Complexity?

```text
O(log n)
```

---

### Binary Search Requirement?

```text
Sorted Data
```

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text
Linear Search
=
Check Every House

Binary Search
=
Keep Dividing City in Half
```

---

# Quick Comparison

| Feature      | Linear Search | Binary Search |
| ------------ | ------------- | ------------- |
| Data Sorted? | No            | Yes           |
| Complexity   | O(n)          | O(log n)      |
| Speed        | Slower        | Faster        |

